        {
            "id": "DJN_DN20250824000763:0",
            "title": "Ansell Announces $200M Buyback as Price Rises Offset Tariffs — Update",
            "description": "<div class=\"body-KX2tCBZq body-pIO_GYwT content-pIO_GYwT\"><div class=\"symbolsContainer-cBh_FN2P logosContainer-cwMMKgmm\" data-no-swipe=\"true\"></div><div><span><p class=\"\"><span>By Stuart Condie</span></p><p class=\"\"><span>SYDNEY--Ansell announced a $200 million on-market buyback after the personal-protective equipment maker's annual profit rose by 33% and it said price rises would fully offset the impact of U.S. tariffs.</span></p><p class=\"\"><span>The Australia-listed company, which reports in U.S. dollars, on Monday reported a net profit for the 12 months through June of $101.6 million, up from $76.5 million a year earlier.</span></p><p class=\"\"><span>Its accounts included a $41.3 million noncash charge against several small brands that it has retired.</span></p><p class=\"\"><span>Revenue rose 24% to $2.00 billion as Ansell, which manufactures the majority of its products in Malaysia, Sri Lanka, Thailand, Vietnam and China, raised U.S. prices to offset the impact of the Trump administration's tariffs.</span></p><p class=\"\"><span>Ansell, which generates more than 40% of its revenue in the U.S., increased prices in June and is doing so again in response to changed tariff rates, Chief Executive Neil Salmon said.</span></p><p class=\"\"><span>\"The announcement of reciprocal tariffs in the U.S. in the second half required decisive action,\" Salmon said. \"While the economic effects of higher tariffs remain unclear, we believe we are well positioned to adapt to this new environment.\"</span></p><p class=\"\"><span>Salmon said that Ansell's manufacturing and sourcing network would give it additional flexibility.</span></p><p class=\"\"><span>The company had already said it could respond to changes in what it called the relative attractiveness of manufacturing locations across its network by redirecting goods rather than shifting production.</span></p><p class=\"\"><span>Earnings per share rose by almost 20% to $1.055, on an adjusted basis. The board declared a dividend of 28.0 cents, up from 21.9 cents.</span></p><p class=\"\"><span>The average analyst forecast had been for a net profit of $135.8 million from revenue of $2.06 billion, according to data compiled by Visible Alpha. Analysts had been looking for adjusted EPS of about $1.24, around the mid-point of the company's $1.18-$1.28 guidance range.</span></p><p class=\"\"><span>Ansell flagged fiscal 2026 adjusted EPS of between $1.33 and $1.45 amid what it called mixed end-market conditions.</span></p><p class=\"\"><span>Industrial sales rose 5.6% on a constant-currency basis to $898.6 million, with earnings lifting 9.9%. Healthcare sales rose 9.4% and earnings increased by just over 10%.</span></p><p class=\"\"><span>Ansell said the personal-protective business it acquired for $635.1 million from Kimberly-Clark in 2024 was performing better than expected, while integration was running ahead of schedule.</span></p><p class=\"\"><span>It upgraded its fiscal 2027 annualized net cost synergies target to $15 million from $10 million, and said it would rebrand some existing products to align with those it had acquired. It logged the brand retirements as a significant item.</span></p><p class=\"\"><span>Write to Stuart Condie at stuart.condie@wsj.com</span></p></span></div></div>",
            "link": "https://www.tradingview.com/news/DJN_DN20250824000763:0/",
